    larger image
    TIFF
    original image

Fig 8. Confusion matrix for the best combinations of feature extractor (CST) and classifier (C-SVC).

The rows represent the true pollen types while the columns indicate how the images have been classified by the computer. All the correct answers are in the diagonal.

https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0157044.g008

With the BOW technique, the M . somnians and T . procumbens pollen grains were correctly classified 32 times (91%), whereas the Faramea and Q . multiflora pollen grains were the worst classified pollen grains, with only 37% of their images being correctly classified ( Fig 9 ). Using the CST + BOW technique ( Fig 10 ), M . somnians presented the highest percentage of correct classifications, which equaled 94% (33 hits), whereas Faramea and Q . multiflora presented the lowest percentages of correct classifications, which was only 37% (13 hits).
